WEBVTT

00:00.065 --> 00:23.320
[SPEAKER_00]: Hello and welcome to Veterans of the Valley.

00:23.340 --> 00:24.402
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm Tom Turbyville.

00:24.922 --> 00:29.927
[SPEAKER_01]: It was natural that Tom Hatfield would write the definitive biography of General Earl Rutter.

00:30.488 --> 00:40.958
[SPEAKER_01]: After all, as a student, he worked summers at the Texas Land Office when General Rutter was its commissioner and later served in an Army Reserve unit that was under Rutter's command.

00:40.978 --> 00:45.243
[SPEAKER_01]: But that's not why Tom Hatfield wrote the book, Rutter from Leader to Legend.

00:45.903 --> 00:50.608
[SPEAKER_01]: See, Tom Hatfield is a lifelong educator and like General Rutter was a college president

00:50.977 --> 00:55.964
[SPEAKER_01]: and now is one of the foremost historians on World War II and military history.

00:56.625 --> 01:05.919
[SPEAKER_01]: He's a senior research fellow at the Dolph Brisco Center for American History at the University of Texas and is director of its military history institute.

01:06.439 --> 01:11.607
[SPEAKER_01]: It is indeed an honor to welcome historian and author Tom Hatfield to Veterans of the Valley.

01:11.707 --> 01:13.930
[SPEAKER_01]: Mr. Hatfield, it is an honor to have you and

01:14.180 --> 01:17.745
[SPEAKER_01]: And thank you for your book on behalf of all lackeys who love General Rutter.

01:17.905 --> 01:18.806
[SPEAKER_01]: It was a labor of love.

01:18.867 --> 01:19.708
[SPEAKER_01]: I enjoyed all of it.

01:19.968 --> 01:20.429
[SPEAKER_01]: Absolutely.

01:20.469 --> 01:24.194
[SPEAKER_01]: Nearly a decade in the research and the writing of the book, as I understand.

01:24.414 --> 01:36.732
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, you could actually say that the research goes back for a half a century when I worked in the land office, as you mentioned, and would see General Rutter then coming and going.

01:36.752 --> 01:44.102
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's a superficial impression, but it was nonetheless useful when I was trying to describe him.

01:44.521 --> 01:54.258
[SPEAKER_01]: Besides your own relationship with General Rudder with the land office and then later serving in the reserves under his command, you're 25 years younger than he was.

01:54.579 --> 02:01.410
[SPEAKER_01]: So why, after writing several books on military history, did you choose this significant biography to be your next project?

02:02.232 --> 02:06.900
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, Rudder had always intrigued me and interested me.

02:06.998 --> 02:14.569
[SPEAKER_00]: For a long time, I thought he was one of the foremost of the battlefield commanders in the war in Europe.

02:16.912 --> 02:26.125
[SPEAKER_00]: But what most people know about him and what I knew about him was what he had done on one day, D-Day, June 6, 1944.

02:27.947 --> 02:30.711
[SPEAKER_00]: And, you know, it was 11 months of war after that.

02:31.231 --> 02:37.279
[SPEAKER_00]: And he was awarded every decoration for valor except the Medal of Honor.

02:37.900 --> 02:42.787
[SPEAKER_00]: And so obviously he had done a lot after that, but it wasn't in the history books.

02:43.067 --> 02:46.212
[SPEAKER_00]: And so I wanted to know what he had done.

02:46.232 --> 02:58.909
[SPEAKER_00]: And then I wanted to know truly what kind of president was he of Texas A&M from 1959 to 1970 when the great transformational changes occurred.

02:59.243 --> 03:06.655
[SPEAKER_00]: So I really wanted to document those two parts of the story of what did he do during the war,

03:06.972 --> 03:09.435
[SPEAKER_00]: and then what he'd done as president of Texas A&M.

03:09.655 --> 03:24.933
[SPEAKER_01]: It was a very definitive time when he was president, and it's so significant that this book does deal with the 11 months, as you say, after Pointe de Hoc, which is still so definitive of his battle service, Pointe de Hoc, and we'll talk about that.

03:25.794 --> 03:31.461
[SPEAKER_01]: I guess every author of nonfiction, 90% of the work is the research involved in it, and you

03:31.745 --> 03:41.375
[SPEAKER_01]: You researched not only at your desk, but by foot, by, as it says in the preface, and I'll just read it very quickly and you can comment on it.

03:41.695 --> 03:47.180
[SPEAKER_01]: With no idea of writing his biography, I interviewed men in England and France who had known him during the war.

03:47.641 --> 03:54.067
[SPEAKER_01]: The Pointe du Hoc battlefield where he emerged as a legendary figure was as familiar as my neighborhood park.

03:54.087 --> 03:55.469
[SPEAKER_01]: So you got to know his every step.

03:56.430 --> 03:58.832
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, I've, while teaching,

03:59.133 --> 04:02.638
[SPEAKER_00]: I've taught in Normandy several times.

04:02.658 --> 04:12.471
[SPEAKER_00]: And while I was there, I went to Pont du Hoc regularly, as well as along Omaha Beach, taking groups of students there.

04:12.872 --> 04:17.438
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's how it really, that's how Pont du Hoc became as familiar to me as it was.

04:17.798 --> 04:22.845
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's probably why, increasingly, Rudder captured my attention.

04:23.551 --> 04:34.343
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk about your first introduction to him as working for him at the Texas land office, which was actually a statewide race that he actually had to win by election.

04:34.723 --> 04:40.269
[SPEAKER_01]: But talk about really your first interaction with him at the land office many years later.

04:40.530 --> 04:43.913
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, you have to understand that he was the boss man.

04:43.953 --> 04:48.759
[SPEAKER_00]: He was a commissioner and I was the lowest of the low.

04:48.939 --> 04:52.883
[SPEAKER_00]: I was a halftime worker.

04:53.268 --> 05:00.456
[SPEAKER_00]: a file clerk and my interaction with him was to see him coming and going in the land office.

05:01.117 --> 05:21.241
[SPEAKER_00]: I did have a couple of, I rode on the elevator with him a couple of times and once I remember that we were alone and it was an awkward moment for me because he was this important person and I was this very unimportant person.

05:21.261 --> 05:22.903
[SPEAKER_01]: I think you built something for him though, right?

05:23.660 --> 05:27.265
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, that was several years later.

05:28.107 --> 05:37.160
[SPEAKER_00]: After I had graduated, I'd gone off to the Army, and I came back to go for graduate study to the University of Texas.

05:37.861 --> 05:47.415
[SPEAKER_00]: And so I was an officer attached to his headquarters, and he was in the commanding general of the 90th Infantry Division.

05:47.435 --> 05:52.603
[SPEAKER_00]: And we were at one of those summer camps at Fort Polk,

05:53.174 --> 06:06.932
[SPEAKER_00]: I was so valuable in the division headquarters that I was assigned responsibility to construct his latrine and given two professional architects and a half dozen other fellows to get the job done.

06:07.152 --> 06:07.653
[SPEAKER_00]: And we did it.

06:07.733 --> 06:08.955
[SPEAKER_00]: And it was an important facility.

06:09.115 --> 06:09.516
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, it was.

06:10.817 --> 06:11.138
[SPEAKER_01]: Indeed.

06:12.339 --> 06:14.242
[SPEAKER_01]: His early years, Eden, Texas.

06:15.023 --> 06:21.932
[SPEAKER_01]: For people who don't know where Eden, Texas is, it's where Highway 87 and 83 cross about 40 miles southeast of San Angelo.

06:22.148 --> 06:32.802
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk about his early years in Eden, and that's where he developed a passion for what would be a part of his early career, and that was the sport of football and really all athletics.

06:34.084 --> 06:35.786
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk about that.

06:35.806 --> 06:43.897
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, Earl was, as his wife Margaret Rudder said to me, Earl was a town boy.

06:45.118 --> 06:47.501
[SPEAKER_00]: The Rudders did not have land.

06:48.523 --> 06:51.767
[SPEAKER_00]: His father was what was known as a commission man.

06:52.321 --> 07:01.493
[SPEAKER_00]: which meant that he would buy and sell almost anything and take as his profit a percentage of the sale.

07:02.173 --> 07:07.320
[SPEAKER_00]: So life was really was a stern struggle economically in the Rudder family.

07:08.461 --> 07:16.692
[SPEAKER_00]: Earl was the fifth of six brothers, that is six brothers who lived.

07:17.352 --> 07:21.838
[SPEAKER_00]: His mother actually gave birth to 13 children.

07:22.072 --> 07:35.709
[SPEAKER_00]: But he was a popular boy around town, seemed to be happy-go-lucky in a town no larger than Eden with population approximately 600.

07:36.591 --> 07:46.643
[SPEAKER_00]: If he or his friends got into mischief, very likely with the social connections between the mothers in the town, his mother would know about it before he got home.

07:47.464 --> 07:51.910
[SPEAKER_00]: And his mother was really the backbone of the

07:52.177 --> 08:21.154
[SPEAKER_00]: of the family insistent upon church attendance and so that's then in 1925 when he was 15 years old Eden had a football team for the first time and there he discovered his passion which was eventually became his ticket the way it took him out of Eden because he was awarded a scholarship to play at the

08:21.674 --> 08:26.921
[SPEAKER_00]: institution we now know as Tarleton State University, which was then a two-year branch of Texas A&M.

08:27.221 --> 08:27.422
[SPEAKER_00]: Right.

08:27.742 --> 08:32.448
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's how he left Eden, and it was football that gave him his handhold on life.

08:34.831 --> 08:38.156
[SPEAKER_01]: Let's fast forward there to Tarleton because he did leave Eden.

08:38.196 --> 08:39.057
[SPEAKER_01]: He went to Tarleton.

08:39.177 --> 08:50.652
[SPEAKER_01]: He played football there, and there was a gentleman that you write about in his book that was probably the first and a very significantly influential person in his life, and that was his football coach, not because of his coaching of X's and O's,

08:51.053 --> 08:52.736
[SPEAKER_01]: Coach W.L.

08:52.796 --> 08:55.822
[SPEAKER_01]: Wisdom, obviously a very important person in Earl Rudder's life.

08:56.523 --> 08:59.468
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, he's Coach W.J.

09:00.110 --> 09:12.893
[SPEAKER_00]: Wisdom, who was not only a self-taught coach with a remarkable one and loss record, but he was also known for his ethics, that he

09:13.092 --> 09:33.160
[SPEAKER_00]: posted where his players would see in the dressing room the great line from the sports writer Grantland Rice that's mostly been forgotten now that when the one great scorer comes to mark beside your name, he cares not whether you won or lost, but how you played the game.

09:34.001 --> 09:36.385
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, Rudder and W.J.

09:36.465 --> 09:41.732
[SPEAKER_00]: Wisdom were great competitors to be sure, but how you played the game

09:42.083 --> 09:49.092
[SPEAKER_00]: How you treated the other players, how you related to the officials of the game were also very important to them.

09:49.112 --> 09:55.600
[SPEAKER_00]: And Wisdom became the Rutter's role model, a positive role model.

09:56.080 --> 09:58.784
[SPEAKER_00]: In some ways, his father was a negative role model.

09:59.104 --> 10:00.045
[SPEAKER_00]: So W.J.

10:00.065 --> 10:03.990
[SPEAKER_00]: Wisdom offset that difference between him and his father.

10:04.375 --> 10:10.502
[SPEAKER_01]: Indeed, you write in the book, from wisdom, Rudder would learn much more than coaching techniques and game strategies.

10:10.522 --> 10:20.553
[SPEAKER_01]: He would gradually absorb the subtleties of managing and motivating young men to perform demanding tasks while working together at the upper limits of their physical exertion.

10:21.094 --> 10:27.941
[SPEAKER_01]: Obviously, this was a precursor to him being a commander in World War II and a president of a university.

10:27.962 --> 10:29.363
[SPEAKER_01]: So it started way back then.

10:29.623 --> 10:30.244
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh, that's right.

10:30.264 --> 10:31.986
[SPEAKER_00]: And the coaching was...

10:32.354 --> 10:42.509
[SPEAKER_00]: just the perfect preparation to command an elite special forces type of unit, the 2nd Ranger Battalion.

10:44.131 --> 10:49.559
[SPEAKER_01]: He entered Texas A&M in 1930, finished in 21 months.

10:49.579 --> 10:54.326
[SPEAKER_01]: When he first arrived, you said in your book that they thought that he was probably sharp enough to finish in three years.

10:54.346 --> 10:57.871
[SPEAKER_01]: He went through A&M and got his degree in 21 months.

10:57.891 --> 11:02.277
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think you said that even in the middle of that, he spent about three months

11:02.780 --> 11:04.182
[SPEAKER_01]: serving in military training.

11:05.183 --> 11:07.887
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, that's right.

11:08.027 --> 11:19.283
[SPEAKER_00]: I found in the registrar's office at Texas A&M the records of the counseling session when he arrived on the campus in September of 1930.

11:19.603 --> 11:26.593
[SPEAKER_00]: And his academic counselor estimated that he would be in the class of 1933.

11:26.978 --> 11:33.546
[SPEAKER_00]: But Rudder took maximum load and more that is course load.

11:34.207 --> 11:37.671
[SPEAKER_00]: He did not go home to Eden in the first summer.

11:37.691 --> 11:38.071
[SPEAKER_00]: He did.

11:38.532 --> 11:41.555
[SPEAKER_00]: He went for summer training as cadets were required to do.

11:42.156 --> 11:51.447
[SPEAKER_00]: And then he returned to the campus and always with numerous part time jobs as well as playing as well as playing football.

11:51.467 --> 11:56.513
[SPEAKER_00]: And so he finished up by graduating in May of 1932, 21 months.

11:56.712 --> 12:23.209
[SPEAKER_01]: right right 1932 you mentioned in your book and you you credit a gentleman that we've had on our show henry dethloff as saying that people who graduated from college in 1932 were probably the hardest hit by the depression and when he graduated he had no job and it you said he had to actually go back to eden just to eat while he was looking for a job that's what he said he said he went all over the state trying to find a job and a job he wanted

12:23.695 --> 12:27.661
[SPEAKER_00]: was coaching high school football and teaching in high school.

12:27.681 --> 12:35.433
[SPEAKER_00]: He had prepared himself to be a football coach while here at Texas A&M as well as to teach.

12:36.114 --> 12:38.677
[SPEAKER_00]: And there were just no jobs available.

12:38.698 --> 12:45.087
[SPEAKER_00]: And so as he told someone years later, in order to eat, he had to go back home.

12:45.107 --> 12:51.036
[SPEAKER_00]: So he went to Eden and got a job, really a pick and shovel job, working on the roads.

12:51.269 --> 12:52.033
[SPEAKER_00]: on the highways.

12:52.133 --> 12:55.489
[SPEAKER_00]: The Texas Highway Department was then building roads across West Texas.

12:55.991 --> 12:57.257
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's what he did the first year.

12:57.297 --> 12:58.181
[SPEAKER_00]: He was out of college.

12:59.909 --> 13:00.773
[SPEAKER_01]: And then

13:01.124 --> 13:10.155
[SPEAKER_01]: He found just down the road, just a little bit southeast of Eden or east of Eden is where it was, a town called Brady, Texas, which obviously meant a lot to him.

13:10.175 --> 13:12.898
[SPEAKER_01]: And that's where he got his first teaching and coaching job.

13:12.918 --> 13:13.919
[SPEAKER_00]: That's right.

13:14.460 --> 13:17.183
[SPEAKER_00]: Brady became his adopted home.

13:18.304 --> 13:26.414
[SPEAKER_00]: And so that's where he was football coach from 1933 to 1938 with a very good record.

13:26.434 --> 13:27.976
[SPEAKER_00]: And he was popular in the town.

13:29.117 --> 13:30.979
[SPEAKER_00]: He was also a very popular teacher.

13:32.579 --> 13:34.782
[SPEAKER_01]: He made a whopping $100 a month for nine months.

13:35.243 --> 13:36.124
[SPEAKER_00]: That's the first year.

13:36.204 --> 13:41.171
[SPEAKER_00]: And a couple of years later, he started getting $110 a month.

13:41.651 --> 13:43.994
[SPEAKER_00]: And he got paid for 10 months rather than nine months.

13:44.155 --> 13:46.057
[SPEAKER_01]: But he was not only coaching football and baseball.

13:46.077 --> 13:47.759
[SPEAKER_01]: He was teaching math, history.

13:48.440 --> 13:48.841
[SPEAKER_00]: Chemistry.

13:48.861 --> 13:49.261
[SPEAKER_00]: Chemistry.

13:50.263 --> 13:51.444
[SPEAKER_01]: For $100 a month.

13:51.464 --> 13:52.706
[SPEAKER_01]: That's right.

13:52.726 --> 13:56.031
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, he said those preparations were really hard.

13:56.311 --> 13:58.754
[SPEAKER_00]: He learned a lot in preparing.

14:00.416 --> 14:02.299
[SPEAKER_00]: And he became the student.

14:02.937 --> 14:07.202
[SPEAKER_00]: as a teacher that he had never been before.

14:07.283 --> 14:14.612
[SPEAKER_00]: And many people have had that experience of learning more while teaching than while being the student.

14:14.632 --> 14:20.860
[SPEAKER_01]: 1933 was a very important year in his life, obviously, because he met a lady named Margaret Williamson, who they called Chick.

14:21.621 --> 14:26.247
[SPEAKER_01]: And they kind of fell in love dancing in the dance halls at Menard, Texas.

14:27.168 --> 14:30.312
[SPEAKER_01]: So obviously that was a union that was very important and very lasting.

14:30.646 --> 14:33.450
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, it was sort of a long-term courtship.

14:33.750 --> 14:47.948
[SPEAKER_00]: They first began meeting to dance, an upscale dance hall type in Menard, Texas, which was sort of between the Williamson Ranch, where she lived, and Eden, where he lived.

14:48.649 --> 14:50.932
[SPEAKER_00]: And that was on through the summer of 1933.

14:52.214 --> 14:54.977
[SPEAKER_00]: But they did not marry until four years later.

14:57.601 --> 14:58.662
[SPEAKER_01]: Talk about...

15:00.143 --> 15:10.678
[SPEAKER_01]: He was at Tarleton, like you said, and he got the head coaching job at Tarleton, that's where I'm going, in the summer of 1938.

15:12.060 --> 15:19.991
[SPEAKER_01]: And he was helped in getting that job by a fellow that a famous building on campus is named after.

15:20.071 --> 15:22.975
[SPEAKER_01]: So talk about the relationship between him and G. Raleigh White.

15:23.215 --> 15:24.497
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, it was a very interesting story.

15:25.899 --> 15:26.860
[SPEAKER_00]: G. Raleigh White,

15:27.008 --> 15:40.186
[SPEAKER_00]: was a very important person around Brady and one of the really major, certainly major land holder in the region and a well-known citizen in Texas.

15:41.447 --> 15:55.446
[SPEAKER_00]: He was then a member of the governing board of Texas A&M and the governing board really had oversight of the appointments to

15:56.135 --> 15:59.419
[SPEAKER_00]: to any one of the components of the Texas A&M system.

16:00.240 --> 16:13.435
[SPEAKER_00]: So when so G. Raleigh White had the potential, in fact, was quite influential in helping Rutter to become the head football coach at Tarleton.

16:13.455 --> 16:20.243
[SPEAKER_00]: The interesting thing about all of this, which shows something of Rutter's character, is that there were two banks in Brady.

16:21.665 --> 16:25.129
[SPEAKER_00]: One was a bank bank on by Mr. White.

16:25.210 --> 16:27.714
[SPEAKER_00]: and there was another bank there as well.

16:28.755 --> 16:38.008
[SPEAKER_00]: A couple of years before, probably 1936, Rudder had gone to Mr. White's bank and made an application for a loan.

16:38.028 --> 16:40.231
[SPEAKER_00]: White was out of town, and it was denied.

16:41.874 --> 16:48.123
[SPEAKER_00]: He then immediately went to the competitive bank, filed his application, and it was approved.

16:48.944 --> 16:51.808
[SPEAKER_00]: And after that, for Rudder's entire life,

16:52.092 --> 16:56.420
[SPEAKER_00]: He banked only with the competitor for Mr. White.

16:56.821 --> 17:05.217
[SPEAKER_00]: He would not compromise, not even when White would be decisive in his appointment to Tarleton.

17:05.778 --> 17:07.722
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think it's an extraordinary story.

17:07.802 --> 17:10.287
[SPEAKER_00]: White helped him, but Rudder never compromised.

17:10.638 --> 17:12.600
[SPEAKER_00]: in his loyalty to the competitive bank.

17:14.702 --> 17:15.943
[SPEAKER_01]: That is an amazing story.

17:16.623 --> 17:23.770
[SPEAKER_01]: I want to move on to his military history because this is a story that certainly is hard to tell in 30 minutes, but we're giving it a try.

17:24.470 --> 17:30.395
[SPEAKER_01]: June of 1941, reported active duty First Lieutenant James E. Rudder, 2nd Infantry Division.

17:30.415 --> 17:32.717
[SPEAKER_01]: Promoted the very next day to captain.

17:32.737 --> 17:40.324
[SPEAKER_01]: And talk about his early military career leading up to, obviously this was before

17:40.777 --> 17:52.770
[SPEAKER_01]: of Pearl Harbor, but then get us into the preparation for the Normandy landing and the final push, and what does define Earl Rudder, and that is the days June 6th through June 8th of Pointe d'Hoppe.

17:53.971 --> 17:55.973
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, you're right.

