[SPEAKER_00]: On January 4, 1944,

20:22.726 --> 20:41.072
[SPEAKER_00]: He was called to General Omar Bradley's headquarters and told that the 2nd Ranger Battalion would, it was essential, that the 2nd Ranger Battalion would make this attack on this impregnable cliffs on the Normandy coast called Pointe du Hoc.

20:41.423 --> 20:46.410
[SPEAKER_00]: and knock out six large German guns that were in place there.

20:46.430 --> 20:53.399
[SPEAKER_00]: And Bradley said it was the most difficult assignment he made to any officer under his command in the entire war.

20:53.419 --> 21:04.815
[SPEAKER_00]: And with Rudder doing it, the 2nd Ranger Battalion being successful, he was thereafter, that's when he became a legend and an icon in the United States Army.

21:06.483 --> 21:31.225
[SPEAKER_01]: One point in the book, and I'll just go over it that I just found fascinating that people don't know, is that this provisional ranger group that was given this assignment, there were three task force A, B, and C, and originally he had assigned himself and his staff to task force C, but the person that he had assigned to command task force A unfortunately got drunk the day before the mission

